[size=16pt][b][color=#FFD700]⏰ TIME-BASED HALVING: THE GAME CHANGER[/color][/b][/size]

[size=12pt][b][color=#FF00FF]The Problem: Performance-Tokenomics Coupling[/color][/b][/size]

[b]Bitcoin's halving schedule:[/b]
[code]if (block_height % 210,000 == 0) {
    reward = reward / 2;
}[/code]

This design assumes [b]constant block production rate[/b]. But what happens when you optimize performance?

[table]
[tr][td][b]BPS[/b][/td][td][b]Halving Frequency[/b][/td][td][b]Economic Viability[/b][/td][/tr]
[tr][td]0.067[/td][td]Every ~47 years[/td][td][color=#FF0000]❌ Too slow[/color][/td][/tr]
[tr][td]100[/td][td]Every ~1 year[/td][td][color=#00FF94]✅ Ideal[/color][/td][/tr]
[tr][td]100,000[/td][td]Every ~9 hours[/td][td][color=#FF0000]❌ DESTROYED[/color][/td][/tr]
[/table]

[b][color=#FF0000]Traditional halving breaks at high performance![/color][/b]

[hr]

[size=12pt][b][color=#00FF94]The Solution: Time-Based Halving[/color][/b][/size]

[b][color=#FFD700]Important Update:[/color][/b] We've adjusted our emission schedule from the earlier 0.5 [size=14pt][b]QUG[/b][/size] per block to a more sustainable time-based model starting at 0.001 [size=14pt][b]QUG[/b][/size] base reward.

Instead of counting blocks, we count [b]elapsed time[/b]:

[code]pub fn calculate_block_reward_time_based(
    genesis_timestamp: u64,
    current_timestamp: u64,
) -> u64 {
    const SECONDS_PER_YEAR: u64 = 31_536_000;
    const BASE_REWARD: u64 = 100_000; // 0.001 [size=14pt][b]QUG[/b][/size]

    let elapsed_seconds = current_timestamp - genesis_timestamp;
    let halving_count = elapsed_seconds / SECONDS_PER_YEAR;

    if halving_count >= 64 {
        return 0; // Emission complete
    }

    // Halving based on TIME, not blocks
    BASE_REWARD >> halving_count
}[/code]

[b][color=#FFD700]Genesis Timestamp:[/color][/b] October 26, 2025, 00:00:00 UTC
[b][color=#FFD700]First Halving:[/color][/b] Exactly one calendar year later
